available.name: available
available.comment:
Returns true if the API is available. The common causes of an API not being avilable are:

  • a permission is missing in the application's manifest.json file
  • the API is defined on a newer version of Chrome then the current runtime

onBeforeNavigate.name: onBeforeNavigate
onBeforeNavigate.comment: Fired when a navigation is about to occur.

onCommitted.name: onCommitted
onCommitted.comment: Fired when a navigation is committed. The document (and the resources it refers to, such as images and subframes) might still be downloading, but at least part of the document has been received from the server and the browser has decided to switch to the new document.

onCompleted.name: onCompleted
onCompleted.comment: Fired when a document, including the resources it refers to, is completely loaded and initialized.

onCreatedNavigationTarget.name: onCreatedNavigationTarget
onCreatedNavigationTarget.comment: Fired when a new window, or a new tab in an existing window, is created to host a navigation.

onDOMContentLoaded.name: onDOMContentLoaded
onDOMContentLoaded.comment: Fired when the page's DOM is fully constructed, but the referenced resources may not finish loading.

onErrorOccurred.name: onErrorOccurred
onErrorOccurred.comment: Fired when an error occurs and the navigation is aborted. This can happen if either a network error occurred, or the user aborted the navigation.

onHistoryStateUpdated.name: onHistoryStateUpdated
onHistoryStateUpdated.comment: Fired when the frame's history was updated to a new URL. All future events for that frame will use the updated URL.

onReferenceFragmentUpdated.name: onReferenceFragmentUpdated
onReferenceFragmentUpdated.comment: Fired when the reference fragment of a frame was updated. All future events for that frame will use the updated URL.

onTabReplaced.name: onTabReplaced
onTabReplaced.comment: Fired when the contents of the tab is replaced by a different (usually previously pre-rendered) tab.

getAllFrames.name: getAllFrames
getAllFrames.comment:
Retrieves information about all frames of a given tab.

chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebNavigation.getAllFrames.details Information about the tab to retrieve all frames from.

Returns: A list of frames in the given tab, null if the specified tab ID is invalid.

getFrame.name: getFrame
getFrame.comment:
Retrieves information about the given frame. A frame refers to an <iframe> or a <frame> of a web page and is identified by a tab ID and a frame ID.

chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebNavigation.getFrame.details Information about the frame to retrieve information about.

Returns: Information about the requested frame, null if the specified frame ID and/or tab ID are invalid.

  • a permission is missing in the application's manifest.json file
  • the API is defined on a newer version of Chrome then the current runtime

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebNavigation.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebNavigation.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebNavigation.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebNavigation.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebNavigation.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebNavigation.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebNavigation.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.
